[* * discussion frames and microworlds]  Some, like Minsky think very hard about the information processing on mental representations.  Other, like Newell who do that as well, are committed to mining the ore of academic psychology for the definition of significant phenomena to be explained.  My aspproach is Piagetian in a profound sense: I am committed to illumintation of learning by tracing the genesis of new intelligence (functioning knowledge) from its immediate predecessors.  I see here no conflict with these other approaches, more of a need for each approach to grow from its own coherent core to that meeting of minds which is a fitting rather than a forcing together.

^^^^^Thus our endeavor in this paper is not to ask "how can we apply this or that idea", but rather to ask "if we take guidance from the observation of behavior, what must we represent in frames to describe cognitive structures and those interactions from which their changes come about ?"

