52^^^One day at the end of The Intimate Study, I visited Miriam in school for a short time.  After she had finished her school work, we played "half-a-game" of checkers because I had to leave: I folded the board in half, we both placed six checkers on our sides and commenced playing. We occasionally played another kind of reduced game, Hexapawn, and contrasted it with Tic tac toe.  Hexapawn is a game of pawn capture played on a three-by-three grid.  Each player starts the game with three pawns and an objective of either capturing  his opponent's three pawns or crossing one of his pawns to the opponent's side of the board.  Hexapawn is an important example because the second player has a significant advantage (the expert second player can't be beaten).  I^cite these activities to show the extent to which playing with variations of standard games was a common activity within the microcultures of my family.  Finally, after the six games of session 10, I interrupted Glenn as he was introducing Miriam to Tic tac toe played on a four-by-four grid.  This background helps to make comprehensible  Miriam's invention of "Tic Tac Toe - Two in a Row":
