65^^^The idea of stages has two essential elements.  First is that different stages characterize discriminable and relatively stable behavior.  Our assumption is that the stability of patterns of behavior derives directly from stability in cognitive structures.  The second element of the stage idea is that there exists a necessary ordering between the successive cognitive structures that generate stable behavior patterns.  If clearly different behaviors deriving from different cognitive structures exist, it must still be decided whether different states are ordered and, if so, for what reason.  The judgment of the reason for apparent order is not a simple one and it does have sgnificant ramifications.  It might be possible that some domains of knowledge exhibit stage like development (and must) and other do not or need not.  In essence, the question is whether regularly observed successions of behavior derive from accidents or from the operation of law-like processes of mental construction.  This is one central question of the study of mind.  

66^^^It is a straightforward task to establish the existence of two different states of Miriam's knowledge about tic tac toe.  We can do this by citing observations focussed on a central facet of her knowledge, her ability to integrate serial and pattern aspects of the game.  Let us first establish that there was a point where she did not integrate serial and pattern aspects of play. Game 4.1 forced Miriam into completing a fork (which she recognized).  
The dialogue recorded with game 4.2 is most revealing of the relative place of
pattern and serial features in her play.  This excerpt suggests that pattern
is ALL she considers:
